Case study: How does a bike-share navigate speedy success?

Introduction

Welcome to the Cyclistic bike-share analysis case study! In this case study, you work for a fictional company, Cyclistic, along with some key team members. In order to answer the business questions, follow the steps of the data analysis process: Ask, Prepare, Process, Analyze, Share, and Act. Along the way, the Case Study Roadmap tables including guiding questions and key tasks will help you stay on the right path.

Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working on the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations

Characters and teams

  • Cyclistic: A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who cant use a standard two-wheeled bike. The majority of riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use the bikes to commute to work each day.

  • Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.

  • Cyclistic marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts who are responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Cyclistic marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Cyclistics mission and business goalsas well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Cyclistic achieve them.

  • Cyclistic executive team: The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the recommended marketing program.

About the company

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a eet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime.

Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the exibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a solid opportunity to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the team needs to beer understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Ask

Three questions will guide the future marketing program:

  1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

  2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?

  3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?

Moreno has assigned you the first question to answer: How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

You will produce a report with the following deliverables:

  1. A clear statement of the business task

  2. A description of all data sources used

  3. Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data

  4. A summary of your analysis

  5. Supporting visualizations and key findings

  6. Your top three recommendations based on your analysis

Case Study Roadmap: Ask Phase

Guiding Questions

  1. What is the problem you are trying to solve?

    • Cyclistic wants to understand how annual members and casual riders use their bike-share system differently to develop strategies that encourage casual riders to purchase annual memberships.

  2. How can your insights drive business decisions?

    • By identifying differences in usage patterns (e.g., trip duration, peak times, preferred stations), Cyclistic can:

      • Tailor marketing campaigns targeting casual riders with specific benefits of membership.

      • Optimize operational strategies, such as bike distribution and station placement, to enhance the user experience.

      • Design membership plans or promotions that align with the needs of casual riders (e.g., flexible plans for weekend users).

Key Tasks

  1. Identify the Business Task

    • Business Task: To analyze the differences in usage patterns between annual members and casual riders to inform strategies for increasing membership conversion and improving service delivery.

  2. Consider Key Stakeholders

    • Primary Stakeholders:

      • Cyclistic Marketing Team: Needs insights to design targeted campaigns for casual riders.

      • Cyclistic Operations Team: Requires data to optimize bike distribution and station management.

    • Secondary Stakeholders:

      • Cyclistic Leadership/Management: Seeks to align findings with broader business goals, such as increasing profitability and market share.

Deliverable

Business Task Statement:
Analyze Cyclistic bike-share usage data to uncover differences in trip patterns, station preferences, and temporal trends between annual members and casual riders. These insights will guide targeted marketing strategies to convert casual riders into members and enhance service efficiency.

Guiding Questions

  1. Where is your data located?

    • The data is located on a publicly accessible Amazon S3 link: Divvy Trip Data.

  2. How is the data organized?

    • The data consists of CSV files, with each file containing trip data for a specific month. Key columns include:

      • ride_id, rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, and member_casual.

    • Data is organized with each row representing a unique trip.

  3. Are there issues with bias or credibility in this data? Does your data ROCCC (Reliable, Original, Comprehensive, Current, Cited)?

    • Reliability: The data is provided by Motivate International Inc., a credible operator of bike-sharing systems.

    • Originality: It is first-party operational data from bike-share usage.

    • Comprehensiveness: Covers detailed trip metrics but lacks demographic or geographic home-location details due to privacy.

    • Currency: The dataset includes the last 12 months, ensuring up-to-date analysis.

    • Citations: Licensing and source attribution are clear.

  4. How are you addressing licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility?

    • The data is publicly licensed under the Divvy Bikes Data License Agreement.

    • Privacy concerns are addressed as personally identifiable information (PII) is excluded.

    • Access is unrestricted and secure via the official data link.

  5. How did you verify the datas integrity?

    • Ensure file completeness (all expected columns present).

    • Check for duplicate or missing entries.

    • Validate date formats and numeric ranges (e.g., coordinates, trip durations).

  6. How does it help you answer your question?

    • This data provides insights into usage patterns, such as trip durations, times, and locations, segmented by rider type (casual vs.members), enabling direct comparisons.

  7. Are there any problems with the data?

    • Limitations:

      • Lack of demographic data prevents insights into user profiles.

      • Incomplete station information in some rows may require imputation or filtering.

    • Challenges:

      • Outliers or incorrect data entries (e.g., negative trip durations) need cleaning.

Follow these steps:

  1. Download the previous 12 months of trip data. Note: If you are planning on using Posits RStudio, use the Divvy 2019 Q1 and Divvy 2020 Q1 datasets. Choosing other data might lead to errors because the data exceeds the memory available in the free plan.

  2. Unzip the files.

  3. Create a folder on your desktop or Drive to house the files. Use appropriate file-naming conventions.

  4. Create subfolders for the .csv file and the .xls or Sheets file so that you have a copy of the original data. Move the downloaded files to the appropriate subfolder.

  5. Follow these instructions for either Excel (a) or Google Sheets (b):

    a. Launch Excel, open each file, and choose to Save As an Excel Workbook file. Put it in the subfolder you created for .xls files.

    1. Open each .csv file in Google Sheets and save it to the appropriate subfolder.

  6. Open your spreadsheet and create a column called ride_length. Calculate the length of each ride by subtracting the column started_at from the column ended_at (for example, =D2-C2) and format as HH:MM:SS using Format > Cells > Time > 373055.

  7. Create a column called day_of_week, and calculate the day of the week that each ride started using the WEEKDAY command (for example, =WEEKDAY(C2,1)) in each file. Format as General or as a number with no decimals, noting that 1 = Sunday and 7 = Saturday.

  8. Proceed to the analyze step.

If you like, continue working with the data to beer familiarize yourself, and perhaps even identify new approaches to answering the business questions.

Final Conclusions

Based on the analysis, we found clear distinctions between the behavior of casual riders and annual members:

  1. Trip Duration: Casual riders tend to have significantly longer trip durations than members, particularly on weekends.

  2. Usage Patterns: Members have a consistent usage pattern throughout the week, while casual riders show a peak in activity during weekends.

  3. Ride Volume: Members account for a significantly higher number of rides overall, indicating regular, frequent usage compared to casual riders.

Top Three Recommendations

  1. Target Casual Riders for Membership Conversion

    • Introduce promotional offers or weekend-specific membership plans to appeal to casual riders. For example:

      • Weekend Memberships with discounts for frequent weekend riders.

      • Highlight benefits of membership, such as cost savings for frequent weekend trips.

  2. Optimize Bike Availability for Casual Riders

    • Increase bike availability and docking stations in popular areas during weekends. This will ensure that casual riders have a seamless experience, increasing their likelihood of returning or converting to membership.

  3. Focus Marketing Efforts on Casual Riders During Peak Times

    • Use data-driven marketing to target casual riders with advertisements and reminders during their peak usage days (Thursday-Sunday). Messaging can emphasize how becoming a member aligns with their current riding patterns.

Next Steps

  1. Share the findings and recommendations with the marketing and operations teams.

  2. Develop and test targeted campaigns, such as a pilot weekend membership program.

  3. Monitor the impact of changes on ride patterns and membership sign-ups to refine strategies.

Additional Data to Expand Analysis

To further refine insights and strategies, it would be useful to:

  1. Incorporate demographic data (e.g., age, gender) to identify specific sub-groups among casual riders.

  2. Analyze weather patterns to see how they influence ride behavior.

  3. Investigate geographic trends (start and end locations) to optimize station placement.
